      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i have a physics exam coming up and i'm a bit stuck on quantum entanglement. can you give me a quick, non-math summary of what it actually is? also i'm confused about how it's different from just regular classical correlation. thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become interconnected in such a way that the state of one particle instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. It's like having a pair of magical dice, where if you roll one and it lands on a six, the other one will always land on a six too, even if it's on the other side of the world. This is different from classical correlation, where two objects might seem related, but their connection doesn't work instantaneously across distances. In classical correlation, it's like having two separate dice that might land on the same number, but only because they were rolled together in the same moment, not because they are magically linked. So, quantum entanglement is like having a magical, instantaneous connection between particles, while classical correlation is like having a regular, non-magical connection.",
